File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function check_overlaps n add_to_simps,  Next: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Prev: Variable all_dotsimp_denoms,  Up: affine

 -- Function: check_overlaps (N, ADD_TO_SIMPS)
     Checks the overlaps thru degree _n_, making sure that you have
     sufficient simplification rules in each degree, for ‘dotsimp’ to
     work correctly.  This process can be speeded up if you know before
     hand what the dimension of the space of monomials is.  If it is of
     finite global dimension, then ‘hilbert’ should be used.  If you
     don't know the monomial dimensions, do not specify a
     ‘rank_function’.  An optional third argument ‘reset’, ‘false’ says
     don't bother to query about resetting things.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Next: Function dotsimp f,  Prev: Function check_overlaps n add_to_simps,  Up: affine

 -- Function: declare_weights (X_1, W_1, ..., X_N, W_N)
     Assigns weights _w_1_, ..., _w_n_ to _x_1_, ..., _x_n_,
     respectively.  These are the weights used in computing ‘nc_degree’.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function dotsimp f,  Next: Function extract_linear_equations [p_1 ... p_n] [m_1 ... m_n],  Prev: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: dotsimp (F)
     Returns 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal generated by the
     equations, i.e., if and only if _f_ is a polynomial combination of
     the elements of the equations.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function extract_linear_equations [p_1 ... p_n] [m_1 ... m_n],  Next: Function fast_central_elements [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Prev: Function dotsimp f,  Up: affine

 -- Function: extract_linear_equations ([P_1, ..., P_N], [M_1, ...,
          M_N])
     Makes a list of the coefficients of the noncommutative polynomials
     _p_1_, ..., _p_n_ of the noncommutative monomials _m_1_, ...,
     _m_n_.  The coefficients should be scalars.  Use
     ‘list_nc_monomials’ to build the list of monomials.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function fast_central_elements [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Next: Function fast_linsolve [expr_1 ... expr_m] [x_1 ... x_n],  Prev: Function extract_linear_equations [p_1 ... p_n] [m_1 ... m_n],  Up: affine

 -- Function: fast_central_elements ([X_1, ..., X_N], N)
     If ‘set_up_dot_simplifications’ has been previously done, finds the
     central polynomials in the variables _x_1_, ..., _x_n_ in the given
     degree, _n_.

     For example:

     set_up_dot_simplifications ([y.x + x.y], 3);
     fast_central_elements ([x, y], 2);
     [y.y, x.x];

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function fast_linsolve [expr_1 ... expr_m] [x_1 ... x_n],  Next: Function grobner_basis [expr_1 ... expr_m],  Prev: Function fast_central_elements [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: fast_linsolve ([EXPR_1, ..., EXPR_M], [X_1, ..., X_N])
     Solves the simultaneous linear equations _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_
     for the variables _x_1_, ..., _x_n_.  Each _expr_i_ may be an
     equation or a general expression; if given as a general expression,
     it is treated as an equation of the form ‘expr_i = 0’.

     The return value is a list of equations of the form ‘[x_1 = a_1,
     ..., x_n = a_n]’ where _a_1_, ..., _a_n_ are all free of _x_1_,
     ..., _x_n_.

     ‘fast_linsolve’ is faster than ‘linsolve’ for system of equations
     which are sparse.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function grobner_basis [expr_1 ... expr_m],  Next: Function list_nc_monomials [p_1 ... p_n],  Prev: Function fast_linsolve [expr_1 ... expr_m] [x_1 ... x_n],  Up: affine

 -- Function: grobner_basis ([EXPR_1, ..., EXPR_M])
     Returns a Groebner basis for the equations _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_.
     The function ‘polysimp’ can then be used to simplify other
     functions relative to the equations.

     grobner_basis ([3*x^2+1, y*x])$
     
     polysimp (y^2*x + x^3*9 + 2) ==> -3*x + 2

     ‘polysimp(f)’ yields 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal generated
     by _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_, that is, if and only if _f_ is a
     polynomial combination of the elements of _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function list_nc_monomials [p_1 ... p_n],  Next: Function mono [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Prev: Function grobner_basis [expr_1 ... expr_m],  Up: affine

 -- Function: list_nc_monomials ([P_1, ..., P_N])
     Returns a list of the non commutative monomials occurring in a
     polynomial _p_ or a list of polynomials _p_1_, ..., _p_n_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function mono [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Next: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Prev: Function list_nc_monomials [p_1 ... p_n],  Up: affine

 -- Function: mono ([X_1, ..., X_N], N)
     Returns the list of independent monomials relative to the current
     dot simplifications of degree _n_ in the variables _x_1_, ...,
     _x_n_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Next: Function nc_degree p,  Prev: Function mono [x_1 ... x_n] n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: monomial_dimensions (N)
     Compute the Hilbert series through degree _n_ for the current
     algebra.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function nc_degree p,  Next: Function set_up_dot_simplifications eqns check_through_degree,  Prev: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: nc_degree (P)
     Returns the degree of a noncommutative polynomial _p_.  See
     ‘declare_weights’.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function set_up_dot_simplifications eqns check_through_degree,  Prev: Function nc_degree p,  Up: affine

 -- Function: set_up_dot_simplifications (EQNS, CHECK_THROUGH_DEGREE)
     The _eqns_ are polynomial equations in non commutative variables.
     The value of ‘current_variables’ is the list of variables used for
     computing degrees.  The equations must be homogeneous, in order for
     the procedure to terminate.

     If you have checked overlapping simplifications in
     ‘dot_simplifications’ above the degree of _f_, then the following
     is true: ‘dotsimp (f)’ yields 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal
     generated by the equations, i.e., if and only if _f_ is a
     polynomial combination of the elements of the equations.

     The degree is that returned by ‘nc_degree’.  This in turn is
     influenced by the weights of individual variables.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: atensor,  Next: cartan,  Prev: affine,  Up: Maxima Core Documentation

1.124 atensor
=============

